---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

export async function getStaticPaths() {
  const posts = {
    "understanding-your-practitioner-suitability-id": {
      title: "What Does an NDIS Practitioner Suitability Mean for You?",
      description:
        "Understanding the importance of the NDIS Suitability assessment and how it protects participants.",
      category: "Clinical Standards",
      date: "2026-01-22",
      readTime: "5 min read",
      tags: ["NDIS Commission", "Suitability", "Quality Assurance"],
      content: `
        <h2>Commitment to Clinical Excellence</h2>
        <p>In the NDIS ecosystem, working with a practitioner who has been deemed <strong>Suitable</strong> by the NDIS Quality and Safeguards Commission marks a commitment to the highest level of accountability.</p>
        <p>As an NDIS Suitable Practitioner (ID: P1636047), my practice meets the rigorous standards of the NDIS Capability Framework, ensuring that participants receive evidence-based support.</p>
        <h3>Direct Accountability</h3>
        <p>Suitable practitioners have a direct responsibility to the NDIS Commission. All plans are developed under strict adherence to the <em>National Disability Insurance Scheme Rules 2018</em>, with a primary focus on human rights and the reduction of restrictive practices.</p>
      `,
    },

    "functional-behaviour-assessment-process": {
      title: "Understanding the Functional Behaviour Assessment Process",
      description:
        "A comprehensive guide to FBA — the foundation of effective, evidence-based behaviour support.",
      category: "Clinical Assessment",
      date: "2025-12-20",
      readTime: "7 min read",
      tags: ["Assessment", "FBA", "Data-Driven"],
      content: `
        <h2>What is Functional Behaviour Assessment (FBA)?</h2>
        <p>An FBA is a systematic process for understanding the 'why' behind behaviours of concern. As a Suitable Practitioner, I use data-driven methods to identify triggers and the functions of behaviour.</p>

        <h3>The FBA Steps</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Stakeholder Interviews:</strong> Collaborating with the participant, family, and support team to gather history and context.</li>
          <li><strong>Direct Observation:</strong> Seeing the participant in their natural environment to identify environmental precursors.</li>
          <li><strong>Data Analysis:</strong> Determining if the behaviour is for communication, sensory needs, or escape/tangible outcomes.</li>
        </ul>
      `,
    },

    "preparing-first-behaviour-support-meeting": {
      title: "Preparing for Your First Behaviour Support Meeting",
      description:
        "What to expect and how to prepare for your initial consultation with a PBS practitioner.",
      category: "Participant Guide",
      date: "2025-11-15",
      readTime: "4 min read",
      tags: ["Getting Started", "Consultation", "NDIS"],
      content: `
        <h2>Setting the Stage for Success</h2>
        <p>The first meeting is about building rapport and understanding the participant’s unique story. It’s a collaborative space where we define goals together.</p>

        <h3>What to Bring</h3>
        <p>To make the most of our time, it is helpful to have copies of the NDIS plan, any recent therapy reports (OT, Speech, or Psychology), and a basic list of current support routines.</p>
      `,
    },

    "signs-ndis-participant-needs-behaviour-support": {
      title: "Signs an NDIS Participant Needs Behaviour Support",
      description:
        "How to identify when Positive Behaviour Support (PBS) is the right choice for a participant.",
      category: "NDIS Navigation",
      date: "2025-11-01",
      readTime: "6 min read",
      tags: ["PBS", "Referral Signs", "NDIS Help"],
      content: `
        <h2>Recognising the Need for Support</h2>
        <p>Positive Behaviour Support is often required when behaviours impact a person’s quality of life, limit their community participation, or pose a safety risk to themselves or others.</p>

        <h3>Key Indicators</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Frequent school or placement suspensions.</li>
          <li>Use of restrictive practices (physical, chemical, or environmental).</li>
          <li>Withdrawal from social activities due to behavioural challenges.</li>
        </ul>
      `,
    },

    /* -----------------------------
       NEW BLOG POSTS (4)
    ------------------------------*/

    "understanding-restrictive-practices-ndis-compliance": {
      title: "Understanding Restrictive Practices Under the NDIS",
      description:
        "A clear guide to regulated restrictive practices, why they occur, and how the NDIS Commission regulates their use.",
      category: "NDIS Compliance",
      date: "2026-02-01",
      readTime: "6 min read",
      tags: ["Restrictive Practices", "Compliance", "NDIS Commission"],
      content: `
        <h2>What Are Regulated Restrictive Practices?</h2>
        <p>Restrictive practices are interventions that limit a person’s rights or freedom of movement. Under the <em>NDIS (Restrictive Practices and Behaviour Support) Rules 2018</em>, these practices are tightly regulated to protect participant safety and uphold human rights.</p>

        <h3>The Five Types of Regulated Restrictive Practices</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Physical restraint</strong> – using physical force to prevent movement.</li>
          <li><strong>Chemical restraint</strong> – medication used primarily to influence behaviour.</li>
          <li><strong>Mechanical restraint</strong> – devices that restrict movement.</li>
          <li><strong>Environmental restraint</strong> – restricting access to areas or items.</li>
          <li><strong>Seclusion</strong> – isolating a person in a room or space.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Compliance Requirements</h3>
        <p>All regulated restrictive practices must be authorised, documented, reported, and paired with strategies to reduce and eliminate their use.</p>
      `,
    },

    "human-rights-positive-behaviour-support": {
      title: "Human Rights in Positive Behaviour Support",
      description:
        "How human rights principles guide ethical behaviour support and protect participant dignity.",
      category: "Practice Framework",
      date: "2026-01-28",
      readTime: "5 min read",
      tags: ["Human Rights", "PBS", "Ethical Practice"],
      content: `
        <h2>Why Human Rights Matter in PBS</h2>
        <p>Positive Behaviour Support is grounded in the belief that every person has the right to autonomy, dignity, and inclusion.</p>

        <h3>Core Human Rights Principles</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Dignity</strong> — respecting identity and lived experience.</li>
          <li><strong>Choice and Control</strong> — participants as active decision‑makers.</li>
          <li><strong>Least Restrictive Practice</strong> — prioritising freedom and independence.</li>
          <li><strong>Participation</strong> — supporting community involvement.</li>
        </ul>
      `,
    },

    "data-collection-behaviour-support": {
      title: "Why Data Collection Matters in Behaviour Support",
      description:
        "A practical guide to collecting meaningful behaviour data and how it improves PBS outcomes.",
      category: "Clinical Assessment",
      date: "2026-01-18",
      readTime: "6 min read",
      tags: ["Data Collection", "FBA", "PBS"],
      content: `
        <h2>The Role of Data in Behaviour Support</h2>
        <p>Accurate data is essential for understanding behaviour patterns and developing effective strategies.</p>

        <h3>Types of Behaviour Data</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>ABC Data</strong> — Antecedent, Behaviour, Consequence.</li>
          <li><strong>Frequency</strong> — how often behaviour occurs.</li>
          <li><strong>Duration</strong> — how long behaviour lasts.</li>
          <li><strong>Intensity</strong> — severity or impact.</li>
        </ul>
      `,
    },

    "support-coordinators-behaviour-support-guide": {
      title: "A Behaviour Support Guide for Support Coordinators",
      description:
        "Key information Support Coordinators need when referring participants for PBS services.",
      category: "NDIS Navigation",
      date: "2026-01-10",
      readTime: "5 min read",
      tags: ["Support Coordinators", "Referral Guide", "PBS"],
      content: `
        <h2>When to Refer for Behaviour Support</h2>
        <p>Support Coordinators play a crucial role in identifying when a participant may benefit from PBS.</p>

        <h3>Common Referral Indicators</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Increased incidents or safety concerns</li>
          <li>Use of restrictive practices</li>
          <li>Placement instability</li>
          <li>Family or carer burnout</li>
        </ul>
      `,
    },
  };

  return Object.keys(posts).map((slug) => ({
    params: { slug },
    props: { posts, slug },
  }));
}

const { posts, slug } = Astro.props;
const post = posts[slug];
const pathname = Astro.url.pathname;

const formattedDate = new Date(post.date).toLocaleDateString("en-AU", {
  year: "numeric",
  month: "long",
  day: "numeric",
});
---

<BaseLayout
  title={`${post.title} | Syed Bokhari`}
  pathname={pathname}
  description={post.description}
>
  <article class="blog-post">
    <header class="article-header">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span class="article-category">{post.category}</span>
          <span class="article-date">{formattedDate}</span>
          <span class="article-read-time">{post.readTime}</span>
        </div>
        <h1 class="article-title">{post.title}</h1>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="article-content">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="content-wrapper">
          <div class="post-content" set:html={post.content} />

          <div class="author-bio">
            <div class="bio-text">
              <p class="bio-kicker">Written By</p>
              <h4>Syed Bokhari</h4>
              <p class="bio-desc">
                <strong>NDIS Behaviour Support Practitioner (ID: P1636047)</strong>.
                Based in Melbourne West with immediate capacity for FBAs and PBS Plans Australia‑wide.
              </p>
              <a href="/referrals" class="btn btn-primary">Make a Referral</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .article-header {
    padding: 5rem 0 3rem;
    background: #f8fafc;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;
  }

  .article-meta {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1rem;
    color: #64748b;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .article-category {
    color: var(--primary);
  }

  .article-title {
    font-size: 2.75rem;
    color: #0f172a;
    line-height: 1.1;
    max-width: 900px;
  }

  .article-content {
    padding: 4rem 0;
  }

  .content-wrapper {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .post-content :global(h2) {
    font-size: 1.75rem;
    margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem;
    color: #1e293b;
  }

  .post-content :global(h3) {
    font-size: 1.4rem;
    margin: 2rem 0 1rem;
    color: #334155;
  }

  .post-content :global(p) {
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: #475569;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    font-size: 1.1rem;
  }

  .post-content :global(ul) {
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    padding-left: 1.5rem;
  }

  .post-content :global(li) {
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    color: #475569;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .author-bio {
    margin-top: 5rem;
    padding: 2.5rem;
    background: #f8fafc;
    border-radius: 16px;
    border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;
  }

  .bio-kicker {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 800;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--primary);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .bio-desc {
    margin: 0.5rem 0 1.5rem;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  .btn-primary {
    background: #1a365d;
    color: white;
    padding: 0.8rem 1.5rem;
    border-radius: 8px;
    text-decoration: none;
    font-weight: bold;
    display: inline-block;
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .article-title {
      font-size: 2rem;
    }
  }
</style>